rComments: This is not a class you can miss lecture or skim through the reading. You have to be in class AND pay attention. You have to read the book AND make connections. If you can do that then w the curve you'll do great. This class helped my GPA alot. And it was very interesting! But your attention span will be tested. Lectures and exams sometimes drag on

If you read this, whatever you do, do NOT take this course. Yes, the course is interesting, but that does not take away from its extreme difficulty. My GPA is currently suffering because of this class, and quite honestly, no matter how smart or interested you are about the media, you will NOT enjoy sitting three hours in Foellinger.

This man is beyond brilliant: he's a modern day Paul Revere or Upton Sinclair, however you like.  Even with a 3 hour lecture, I was captivated from beginning to end every time.  Then again, I'm a force of intellect, most of the class looked like they wanted to die.

This class required a lot of reading and attention during class, but Professor McChesney is amazing at articulating media critique and the reform that is available if taken advantage of. It's a difficult class, but it is by far the best class I have taken on campus thus far.

I loved this class. Yes, it's difficult, but it really isn't impossible. The thing about it that sucks is that McChesney gives you 1 week to write an 8-10 page paper, which sucks but someone who is motivated enough can do it. I found the subject material and the books to be extremely interesting, and so were the lectures. Bring your laptop to class

3 hour class made me want to gouge my eyes out. He makes a big deal about needing read the books to do well on the papers, but I was able to do alright just by reading the summaries on B&N. Funniest part of the class: made about 6 different colored exams for and final, but they were all exactly the same- same questions, same order.
Class is extremely long and boring. Material is interesting through the readings. However, exams concentrate on lecture. DO NOT skip lecture.

HORRIBLE PROFESSOR. He was unbearably dull, had no clue how to teach... or even keep people awake. Tests were terrible, TA's graded harshly, and even the assigned readings were intolerable. WORST CLASS I HAVE TAKEN IN 4 YEARS.

McChesney is not only a pioneer in the democracy of the media but is passionate about teaching this subject. Lectures are long and they can kinda of drag on; missing even one is not advised. Must do the readings thoroughly and there is a lot of writing but this is one of the most valuable courses you can take on campus.

This was by far the most difficult and lengthy class I ever took toward my degree, but by far the most worthwhile.  Bob McChesney is one of the smartest men at U of I, with a real sense of the communications industry, both good and bad.  I would highly recommend him to anyone, regardless of major.  Watch a documentary that features him:  "OutFOXed"

Hard hard class! I read everything and studied my ass off and still got a B+. Also, he makes you stay the entire 3 hours and the TAs grade crazy hard! I've taken many upper level communications, political science, and advertising classes and this has been the hardest. DON'T TAKE IT!!!

This class had quite a bit of reading, but it was an awesome class.  He definitely knows his stuff and really cares about what he is teaching.  I wish he taught more classes than this.  I'd gladly take another class he taught.

This class was tough. there was a lot of information and you actually stay for the full 3 hours, but it was really interesting stuff and the 3 papers were really easy to write (i didn't do any of the reading and still got a perfect score on them)

By far, one of the smartest professors as well as most intellectually-stimulating and entertaining. Quite a bit of work involved--readings were independent of lecture, papers were length as were essay exams--but the coursework is truly interesting, and if you can keep up, he'll keep you engaged the entire time. Best course I've taken in 4 years.

McChesney is the man. Well, he's not THE man. You know what I mean.
stay away from comm 264 if you can.
